data.name: createMaskButton.ToolTip
data.value: Allows you create a region of interest based on the first frame of a video file you select. You can draw the region of interest with your mouse and motion detection will be constrainted to just that part of each video frame. A small region of interest speeds up motion detection, while a large or no region of interest slows it down.

data.name: sensitivityUpDown.ToolTip
data.value: Controls how many pixels in total need to change between video frames (after all filters have been applied) in order for it to be considered motion. Higher values will detect less motion. This is a setting you may need to tweak until you get it right. Sorry. :(

data.name: continuationUpDown.ToolTip
data.value: Controls how many times the configured sensitivity has to be exceeded in succession before motion is confirmed and the degree of activity is increased. Increase to filter out short events like insects or birds quickly flying past the camera.

data.name: maxDeviationUpDown.ToolTip
data.value: Controls how concentrated to a single area any motion has to be. Lower values mean that motion has to be in a very constrained area, while higher values allow for more spaced out motion throughout the scene, which could lead to more false positives (e.g. during snowfall or when sunlight hits the camera lens).

data.name: thresholdNumericUpDown.ToolTip
data.value: Controls how sensitive motion detection is to changes between individual frames in a video file. This is used to remove noise. Higher values decrease the sensitivity (changes between frames need to be significant) and lower values increase it.
